:::.col-12 .col-md-6
* In the 1800s, it was recognized that street lights that burned gas could cause neighboring plants `to develop short, thick stems and shed their leaves`. In 1901, Dimitry Neljubow identified that a byproduct of gas combustion was ethylene gas and that this gas could affect plant growth.
* R. Gane later showed that this same gas was naturally produced by plants and caused `faster ripening of many fruits`.
* `Gaseous` in form and rapidly diffusing.
* Gas produced by one plant will affect nearby plants.
